<oauth2_oidc_security_guide>
<title>OAUTH 2.0 / OPENID CONNECT SECURITY TESTING</title>

<critical>OAuth 2.0 and OpenID Connect are the foundation of modern authentication and authorization. Implementation flaws can lead to account takeover, unauthorized API access, and data exposure. The complexity of these protocols creates numerous attack surfaces across authorization servers, clients, and resource servers.</critical>

<scope>
- Authorization Code flow (with and without PKCE)
- Implicit flow (deprecated but still deployed)
- Client Credentials flow
- Resource Owner Password Credentials flow
- Device Authorization flow
- Token handling (Access, Refresh, ID tokens)
- OpenID Connect claims and scopes
- Social login integrations
</scope>

<methodology>
1. Map OAuth/OIDC endpoints and identify supported flows.
2. Test redirect_uri validation for open redirect and token theft.
3. Examine state/nonce parameters for CSRF and replay attacks.
4. Analyze token handling for validation gaps and misuse.
5. Test scope escalation and cross-client token usage.
</methodology>

